<TITLE> Thai king opens Bangkok landmark in rare appearance </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BANGKOK, Sept 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Thailand's revered King Bhumibol Adulyadej made an increasingly rare public appearance on Wednesday, presiding over the celebration of Bangkok's newly renovated landmark, the 223-year-old Giant Swing. The renovation of the twin 21-metre (69 ft) teak poles, repaired over two years using six century-old teak trees, was done as part of celebrations to mark his 80th birthday in December. King Bhumibol, the world's longest serving monarch who marked 60 years on the throne last year, and Queen Sirikit were greeted by thousands of Thais at the Buddhist-Brahmin ceremony, many waving national flags and shouting "Long Live the King". The King moved slowly during his 45-minute stay at the ceremony near the Giant Swing, built after a new royal dynasty was established in Bangkok in 1782. King Bhumibol has cut back his public appearances since undergoing a back operation in July 2006. Thailand's constitutional monarchy has few formal powers, but the reverence with which the King is held means that his rare comments on politics are highly influenti
